{
  "texts": [
    "For i ̸ = j, X ij + X ji = 1, X ij ∈ D. This together with the assumption that all players are equally strong (i.e., X ij are equally distributed) is equivalent to 0 < P (X ij = a) = P (X ij = 1 -a) for any a ∈ D. Under such a model, Propositions 1 and 2 still hold.",
    "However, the local limit theorem used in the proof of Proposition 3 (Claims 1 and 2), which holds for integer-valued random variables, should be extended to this case.",
    "One possible direction is to derive the local limit theorems, as was done in number theory (Alon and Freiman, 1988), by using the circle method."
  ]
}